column168: EnviroServe was dispatched to the site. Upon the contractor’s  arrival, personnel  observed  that the  released  material  impacted  two  10ft-by-28ft area  of the trailer  floors  and  a  10ft-by-30ft  area of  concrete  terminal  floor.  EnviroServe  personnel  estimated that twenty-five (25) gallons of material was released.  EnviroServe personnel stated that the asphalt parking  lot  under  the  trailers  were  also  impacted  in  an  area  of  20ft-by53ft.  EnviroServe  personnel neutralized the impacted areas and used granular absorbents to collect the material. The 225 gallons remaining in the damaged poly tote was transferred into a new tote to forwarded on to the consignee. The spent absorbents and debris were placed into six (6) 55-gallon poly drum and was staged onsite at  the  terminal  prior  to  the  contractor  demobilizing.

column168: On 3/6/2023, a Non-Accident Release involving GATX36187, a loaded tank car of Sulfuric Acid, spent, un1832, was observed leaking from the service equipment housing at the top of the car. The car was isolated and Brandon Davis a representative of Phillips 66, (504-416-7580, Brandon.J.Davis@p66.com was notified. The National Response Center, Indiana DEM, and CHEMTREC (Report# 2023-0306-00286) were also notified. HEPACO, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the liquid valve in the open position and the secondary closure not in place resulting in a hazardous materials release. The issue was identified, and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper representative, Brandon Davis. Contractor personnel positioned the valve in the closed position, installed and secured the 4-bolt flange secondary closure and cleaned up released product impacting the tank car and the ballast below. The car was released for transportation. This incident did not require a special switching move. 7.1 not required. Cause Code:254 NARRI:110

column168: At 0829 EST, ERTS was contacted by XPO Logistics (UTU) about a cargo release. It was reported that due to a forklift puncture approximately 0.5 gallon of PPG Amerlock 400V Cure (Hazardous - UN3470) was released. The caller stated that the released product was contained to the trailer floor at dock door #30. The terminal requested a contractor out for cleanup and containment. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 0.5-gallons of product released to the packaging and inner box due to a forklift puncture. Absorbents were deployed and worked into the impacted area. The box containing 4 impacted pails, shrink wrap, and absorbents were containerized into a 55-gallon poly drum. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage. The unimpacted (12) 1-gallon pails were placed inside a 55-gallon poly drum to be sent on to the customer due to no other packing being available.
Other Fell

On 3/3/23, the Y SPO1011 03 was working on the east end of Hauser yard. During their work, the crew noticed locomotive diesel fuel leaking out of the bottom of the TCBX 286060, listed as line 18 in track 3509. It was at this time that the crew notified the yardmaster who immediately notified BNSF mechanical and transportation officers on site. BNSF Mechanical promptly contacted the BNSF Hazmat team and began an active investigation into the leak and to apply containment.  The BOV was found with an ice plug in the broken BOV cap with damage to the closed BOV.  Fuel was recovered into a vacuum truck while a transload of remaining fuel occurred to another car.   An estimated 7,768 gallons was released from the car with approximately 6,350 gallons reaching soil.  Spilled fuel impacted tracks 3509 and 3510.  Investigation into extent of fuel impacts to soil and remediation began immediately.  Soil impacts and remediation are being coordinated with ID DEQ.

column168: At 1511 ET, XPO terminal UDV reported a spill that occurred inside a trailer located in Henderson, CO. The spill consisted of (1) 270-gallon plastic tote of NA1993 "Huskie EC347", which was punctured by another pallet while unloading cargo from the trailer, causing the tote to release. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct containment and cleanup. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 50-gallons of product released to a 2' x 53' area of the trailer floor and a 4' x 4' area of the concrete lot due to a puncture. The material was transferred into a new tote. Absorbents were deployed and worked into the impacted areas. column168: On March 01, 2023, one (1) 5-gallon pail of 722 NO.2 PLANET THINNER (UN1263) was damaged during a load shift and released approximately two (2) gallons of product to the trailer interior. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from GrayMar Environmental Services (GES) to remediate the impacted surface. GES personnel contained the damaged pail of paint thinner in one (1) 55-gallon drum, then deployed absorbents to the released material. The crew then used hand tools to collect all paint thinner-impacted material in one (1) 55-gallon drum for disposal by R+L.

On March 06, 2023, one (1) 5-gallon container containing UN1760 was punctured by a forklift and released approximately two (2) gallons of product to the trailer interior. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from First Call Environmental (FCE) to remediate the impacted surface. FCE personnel utilized granular absorbents and hand tools to remove any product and containerized all waste into one (1) 35-gallon poly drum for transport and disposal.

column168: On 3/8/23 at approximately 1900 Dangerous Goods Administration received a call from  Employee 261690 at the hub facilty in Anchorage, reporting an undeclared dangerous goods spill.  The shipment consisted of 3 fiberboard boxes, each containing Part A and part B of moisture vapor barrier primer.  One of the packages were discovered leaking during sort.  Further investigation revealed that the inner contents has completely spilled; cause unknown.  The shipment wad tendered under Special Provision A197, however, the inner contents exceed the maximum amount allowed under the Special Provision.  As a result, this shipment is classifed as an undeclared dangerous goods shipment.  The two accompanying package have been delivered.  The damaged shipment has been placed in a salvage drum, being prepared fro disposition.

column168: XPO terminal USE notified ERTS of a 1 cup release of UN1814 "Nalco BC1604" from a 15-gallon poly drum due to improper loading by the previous terminal, impacting the side of the drum and pallet. ERTS dispatched a contractor for cleanup and containment.  Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 1-cup of product released to the side of the 15-gallon poly drum due to a damaged cap. A second 5-gallon poly drum of product was also damaged. The 15-gallon drum and 5-gallon pail were each placed into a 55-gallon and 30-gallon poly drums. All absorbent pads and PPE were containerized into a 15-gallon poly drum. All waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column168: At 1028 ET, XPO terminal XFW contacted ERTS to report a spill that occurred inside of a trailer and on the dock, in Ft. Wayne, IN. The spill consisted of a 330-gallon plastic tote containing UN2735 AO-24, which was being unloaded off the trailer when XPO personnel noticed a trail of liquid leading up to the dock, and it then began gushing once it was set down. The terminal coned off the area. ERT dispatched a contractor for cleanup assistance. Contractors arrived onsite at 1255 ET. Crew confirmed approximately 3-gallons of product released to an 8' x 8' area of the dock floor and a 2' x 15' area of the trailer floor. Contractors stated the side of the tote was cracked due to a possible puncture occurring as a result of load shift. The material was transferred from the damaged tote into a new one. Absorbents were deployed and worked into the impacted areas. The damaged tote was then cut up and containerized along with all impacted absorbents into (3) 55-gallon poly drums. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column42: LITHIUM ION BATTERIES CONTAINED IN EQUIPMENT INCLUDING LITHIUM ION POLYMER BATTERIES
column168: AT THE UPS FACILITY IN COLOGNE, GERMANY THE PACKAGE WAS FLAGGED DURING X-RAY AS A POTENTIAL  UNDECLARED DANGEROUS GOODS. PACKAGE INSPECTION REVEALED 25 MOBILE PHONES WITH INSTALLED LITHIUM ION BATTERIES. THE OUTER BOX HAS TWO AREAS WHERE IT APPEARS UNKNOWN MARKINGS OR LABELS HAVE BEEN CUT FROM THE BOX. ADDITIONALLY, THERE WAS GREEN US CUSTOMS AND BORDER "EXAMINED BY" TAPE AT THE PACKAGE CLOSURE. THERE IS AN ORANGE FRAGILE HANDLE WITH CARE STICKER ON THE OUTER BOX. THERMAL TRACKING LABEL SHOWS A DESCRIPTION OF CELL PHONES. INVOICE BREAKS DOWN CONTENTS AS 8 X SAMSUNG S8, 7 X SAMSUNG GALAXY S8 PLUS, AND 10 SAMSUNG GALAXY S9 PLUS. THE PACKAGE WAS SHIPPED FROM FLORIDA TO GAMBIA USING UPS ACCOUNT 2061V7, TELLFIX INC, 4815 E BUSCH BLVD, SUITE 102, TAMPA FL, 33617.

THE SHIPPER HAS VIOLATED THE ADDITIONAL REQUIREMENTS OF PACKING INSTRUCTION 967 SECTION II SINCE THE CONSIGNMENT IS OVER TWO PACKAGES. THE REQUIRED LITHIUM BATTERY MARK IS MISSING. ADDITIONAL TRACKING NUMBERS TO THE SAME CONSIGNEE ARE 1Z972E593528815595, 1Z972E593525857180, 1Z972E593520178173, 1Z972E593524554615 AND 1Z972E593533982565. column168: SequenceEvent: THE AREA MANAGER NOTICED THIS PACKAGE LEAKING IN THE TRAILER AND CALLED QA OVER TO TAKE CARE OF THE HAZMAT.  QA RUSHED OVER TO THE AREA TO INVESTIGATE.  UPON ARRIVAL, QA NOTICED THE PACKAGE WAS LOADED UPSIDE DOWN IN THE TRAILER AND LEAKING OUT.  QA CALLED OVER THE AREA MANGAER AND THE SORT MANAGER TO LET THEM KNOW TO PULL THE TRAILER OFF AND MOVE IT CLOSER TO QA SO THEY CAN CLEAN UP THE AREA SAFELY.  ONCE THE TRAILER WAS ON THE QA DOOR, QA PLACED THE PACKAGE IN THE RED TOTE WHICH WAS LINED WITH A CLEAR, LARGE HAZMAT BAG AND PLACED NEUTRALIZER AND FOLD ABSORB DOWN TO CLEAN UP THE AREA.  ONCE IT WAS CLEAN AND SAFE, QA PLACED A LOAD NET UP AND THE TRAILER GOT BUMPED BACK OVER TO THE OUTBOUND DOOR TO KEEP GETTING LOADED DOWN. DescribePack: THE PACKAGE WAS LOADED UPSIDE DOWN ON THE LEFT SIDE OF THE TRAILER WHICH LED TO ONE OF THE BOTTLES LEAKING OUT THRU THE CAPS. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: THE PACKAGE WAS PLACED IN A TOTE LINED WITH A CLEAR HAZMAT BAG AND CLEANED UP WITH NEUTRALIZER AND FOLD ABSORB.

column168: On March 16, 2023, at 1000 ET, XPO Logistics Terminal XCJ experienced a 5-gallon release of UN1263 “Certi-Vex AC 1315 Super Seal HG” from a 5- gallon metal drum due to a puncture caused by other freight. No soils, drains, or waterways were impacted. ERTS dispatched Hepaco for cleanup operations. On March 16, 2023, at 1150 ET, Hepaco arrived on site and confirmed approximately 5-gallons of product released to an 8’ x 6’ area of the trailer floor and a 3’ x 3’ area of the concrete lot below the trailer. Hepaco confirmed the pail was punctured by adjacent freight. Absorbents were deployed and worked into the impacted areas. The empty damaged pail was containerized into a 55-gallon metal drum. All spent absorbents and cleanup debris were containerized into a separate 55-gallon metal drum. All waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

XPO contacted ERTS to report that there had been a 20-ounce spill of UN1814 "Clean-R-235" potassium hydroxide, a solution that was released from one 275-gallon plastic tote. XPO stated that the material impacted the trailer floor. ERTS dispatched a contractor to complete cleanup. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 2-cups of product released to a 1' x 1' area of the trailer floor which had evaporated. The tote appeared to be damaged due to a forklift puncture. The product was transferred from the damaged tote into a new one. Soda ash was deployed to clean and neutralize the trailer floor. The damaged tote was then cut up and containerized along with cleanup debris into a 55-gallon poly drum. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

Material was found on top of damaged freight that had leaked previously and dried, (3) 55-Gallon drums released (1) pt. due to pressure build up, faulty containers. The spill was cleaned and all material placed into overpack for proper disposal.

On March 07, 2023, one (1) 270-gallon tote containing UN3082 was damaged and released approximately 150 gallons of product to the trailer interior, dock floor, and pavement beneath the trailer. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from Hazmat Special Services (HMSS) to remediate the impacted surfaces. HMSS personnel transferred the remaining virgin product to a new 330-gallon tote for continued shipping. The crew used absorbents to clean off the impacted tote and contained all waste in fifteen (15) 55-gallon drums for disposal.   On March 08, 2023, HMSS returned to the site and utilized a power washer to finish remediating the site and contained all UN3082-impacted water in the previously mentioned drums.

There were 2 canisters of Bovine Semen each banded on their own plastic skid. They were loaded on a maindeck pallet up on the high side of the contour by FRA. Our warehouse agent working Import breakdown, came up to the pallet and began to forklift one of the pieces from the pallet (they weigh around 70 plus kgs each). When he was backing up the forklift bounced a little from the motion of moving from the roller-mat area to the warehouse floor and the piece fell over to the side and on the ground because of the flimsy skid it was on. He immediately notified the Supervisor and the area was cordoned off and the fire department was contacted. After the fire department assessed the situation they said it was ok for us to call our Haz clean up team who came in put the package into a recover drum without a lid on top.
column169: We have taken statements from those involved and I also went through the CCTV in regards to this incident. The agent was spoken to on the handling of this shipment and advised that in the future, a spotter must be used to ensure that the piece is secured during the removal process from the pallet or that a solid skid is brought next to the pallet and the piece is slid over by 2 agents onto it. He agreed that he would practice this method in the future.

column168: When serving industry, crew noticed tank car already in place leaking from bottom.  Crew reported this and left location.  NS Haz Mat  & contractor responded and found the bottom outlet valve closed and pinned in place, but liquid dripping from around cap.  When checked, the bottom outlet cap was not even hand tight.  Car was parially unloaded the previous Friday and the cap was not properly secured.  Car also had HOME SHOP stickers applied, but there was no notation on the waybill that car was moving under OTMA.  Cap was secured with wrench and leak stopped.  SHipper contacted to explain why HOME SHOP stickers were applied.

At 0956 ET, XPO notified ERTS of a cargo release at terminal XSC. It was reported that approximately 1 cup of UN3266 Cir Kleen No. 265 was released from a 55-gallon plastic drum. The release impacted the inside of trailer #3112327. ERTS dispatched a contractor to the site to complete cleanup activities. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 1-cup of product released to a 4' x 4' area of the trailer floor due to a damaged/fault cap. Absorbents were deployed and worked into the impacted area. The damaged drum and cleanup debris was collected into a 95-gallon poly over pack. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

UTLX 211632 was found releasing by the FRA in the UPRR Nampa yard. Graymar Environmental responded, found one swing bolt less than tool tight resulting in approximately 1/2 gallon released. Graymar replaced the nozzle gasket, secured the manway swing bolts, and decontaminated the car.
During an FRA inspection the inspector found NATX 302721 had leaked, the leak appeared to be from the Manway. Response found the Manway gasket was deteriorated and was not sealing the closure.

column168: On March 9, 2023, at 1510 ET, Emergency Response and Training Solutions (ERTS) was contacted by Landstar Inway personnel in Amarillo, Texas regarding the release of approximately 5 gallons of Busan 1078 Biocide (Corrosive Liquid, acidic, organic, n.o.s., UN3265, 8, II) from (1) 275-gallon plastic tote.  The release was reportedly due to a puncture to the tote from a ratchet strap.  No drains or waterways were reported as affected by the release.  Contractors transferred the remaining product from the damaged tote to a new one to be forwarded on to the consignee.  Contractors then cleaned up the release using absorbents, hand tools, and the proper PPE.  The released product, spent absorbents, and all other waste debris generated from the release were containerized in (1) 55-gallon poly drum.  The damaged tote, in addition to the previously mentioned poly drum were then taken offsite by the contractor for proper disposal.

On March 16, 2023, at 1205 ET, Emergency Response and Training Solutions (ERTS) was contacted by Hub Group personnel in Duncan regarding the release of approximately 100 gallons of Hardener for 2K-Premium-Clear Saphir (Resin solution, n.o.s., UN1866, 3, III) from (2) 300-gallon plastic totes.  The release was reportedly due to a forklift puncture.  No drains or waterways were reported as affected by the release.  Contractors were dispatched to clean up the release using absorbents, hand tools, and the proper PPE.  The damaged totes were cut up and placed in waste drums along with all other waste debris generated.  A total of (10) 55-gallon metal drums and (1) 55-gallon plastic drum of waste were generated from this release.  The waste drums were then taken offsite by the contractor for proper disposal.

LEAKING PACKAGE ON A CHUTE OF A LOADING DOCK. A SUPERVISOR WHO DISCOVERED THE PACKAGE CALLED A DESIGNATED RESPONDER FOR CLEAN UP. A RESPONDER WENT TO THE LOCATION OF THE SPILL WEARING FULL PPE (GOGGLES, BOOTS, APRON, GLOVES AND SILVER SHIELD INNER LINER, AND SLEEVES). THE OUTSIDE OF THE PACKAGE WAS LABELED WITH THE FLAMMABLE LIQUID DOT DIAMOND. THE DESIGNATED RESPONDER USED THE REVISED JANUARY 2021 DECISON TREE AND RESPONSE SHEET FOR FLAMMABLE LIQUIDS. THEN BY FOLLOWING THE RESPONSE STEPS, THE RESPONDER ADDED CLAY BASED ABSORBENT TO THE LIQUID USED TO SOLIDIFY THE LIQUID COMPLETELY. THEN IT WAS SWEPT UP WITH BROOM AND PLASTIC DUSTPAN AND PLACED INTO A LINED SPILL TRAY WITH THE PAKCAGE. MATERIALS WERE BROGUHT TO THE PSC FOR FURTHER PROCESSING USING THE WASTE DISPOSAL FOR A FULL DMP.

column168: A LEAKING PACKAGE WAS DISCHARGED FROM PD5 CONVEYOR BELT TO BAY 308 AND WAS FOUND BY THE LOADER. THE LOADER DID NOT TOUCH THE PACKAGE AND NOTIFIED THE SUPERVISOR IMMEDIATELY AND CALLED A DESIGNATED RESPONDER TO CLEAN IT UP. THE DESIGNATED RESPONDER DONNED FULL PPE (APRON, GOGGLES, BOOTS, GLOVES X 3 AND SILVER SHIELD LINER, AND SLEEVES). THE RESPONDER TOOK A FULLY STOCKED SPILL CART TO THAT LOCATION SOON AFTER. THE PACKAGE WAS ON THE GRATING AND HAD A LIMITED QUANTITY LABEL ON IT. THE RESPONDER USED THE REVISED JANUARY 2021 DECISION TREE AND LIMITED QUANTITY RESPONSE SHEET. THE LIQUID WAS PH TESTED USING PH INDICATOR TAPE BUT DID NOT REGISTER. THEN THE RESPONDER USED THE FLAMMABLE LIQUID RESPONSE SHEET. THE LIQUID WAS NOT CONTAMINATED THE CARDBOARD AND DID NOT NEED TO BE SOLIDIFED. IT WAS TRANSPORTED BACK TO THE PSC FOR PROCESSING USING THE WASTE DISPOSAL FOR A FULL DMP. THE PACKAGE WAS PROCESSED COMPLETELY TRHOUGH THE DMP AND ONE BAG WAS MADE. DECON OF PPE WAS FOLLOWED USING CHECKLIST.

Plant personnel noticed material leaking from a super sack. Profile # 97-9088 shipped on #024447678JJK.  When the leak was detected the super sack and pallet were placed on a containment pallet. Cleanup contractor was called to have the material in the SSK be repackaged into drums.   Supersack did not have inner liner and material contained limited amount of liquids from wet filter materials. An estimated 1/2 gallon leaked out of the SSK and most of the material was soaked up by a cardboard pad on the pallet.  Customer was contacted and confirmed that supersack will have inner liners.
column169: Recommend to the customer to prevent possible future issues, either use poly drums, lined CYBs or lined Supersacks for future loads.  Customer confirmed that future loads will be within lined supersacks and drying procedure completed before adding into waste container for off-site transportation.

On March 09, 2023, one (1) 55-gallon drum containing UN1993 was punctured by a forklift and released approximately three (3) cups of product to the top of the drum. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services LC who dispatched a crew from Ancon Services (AS) to assess and remediate the site. AS personnel utilized cleaning materials and placed all UN1993-impacted material into one (1) poly overpack.

On March 09, 2023, one (1) 55-gallon drum of UN3264 was punctured by a forklift and released approximately 15-gallons of product to the trailer floor and asphalt parking lot. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from Thin Line Environmental (TLE) to remediate the site. TLE personnel patched the impacted drum then utilized a 95-gallon overpack to contain the damaged 55-gallon drum. The crew then utilized absorbents, degreaser, and hand tools to remediate the surface, then containerized all UN3264-impacted material in four (4) 35-gallon drums for disposal by R+L.

ABF city driver picked up this HM shipment from the shipper's dock.  The shipper loaded the freight into the ABF trlr.  While loading the freight the leaking drum had a pallet pushed into the bottom of the drum.  There is no visible hole in the drum but it has leaked a quart of the product onto the floor of the ABF trlr.  The leak was noticed by a 269 checker.  The spill inside the trlr was cleaned with staydry.

column168: SequenceEvent: Shipment taken out of system flow due to external carton wet. The package came off the Trailer #695774 already wet leaking and damage from the unloaded.  The package was placed in a lined red tote and taken to the hazmat cage. Upon inspecting the inner contents there were 4 x 1 gallon plastic bottles of Ethanol 140 Proof. The 1-one  gallon plastic bottle of Ethanol had a cap that was not sealed properly causing .40 gallons to release. A corrugated liner  was used on the top of bottles for packing. Facility procedures for damaged hazardous materials followed contents contained and awaiting disposition. DescribePack: The one - 1 gallon plastic bottle of Ethanol 140 proof had a cap that was not sealed properly on bottle causing .40 gallons to release. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: Package was placed in a red lined tote to contain the leaking package and taken to the hazmat cage.

column42: PRINTING INK, FLAMMABLE OR PRINTING INK RELATED MATERIAL (INCLUDING PRINTING INK THINNING OR REDUCING COMPOUND), FLAMMABLE
column168: During the inspection process at the PWKA station the employee noticed that the package was leaking.  Inside of the outer package there were 6 inner packages of UN1210 Printing Ink that had leaked.  DG Admin instructed them to place the package in a drum, and to contact the shipper for disposition.

The shipment was discovered to be leaking while on the road by the courier.  It was brought back to the station and brought to the attention of the manager.  There were no hazard labels or markings on the outside of the package, however there were GHS labels that led DG Admin to research the product to verify if it was a dangerous good.  DG Admin received an email from the manufacturer that contained the SDS for the product and it confirmed that it is UN3082 Environmentally Hazardous Substance, liquid, 9, PGIII.  Each inner container is greater than 5kg.    DG Admin advised the station to place the drum into a salvage drum and to hold until further notice.

column42: AEROSOLS, POISON, PACKING GROUP III (EACH NOT EXCEEDING 1 L CAPACITY)
column168: On 3/17/2023 at approximately 0835, Dangerous Goods Adminstration received a call from Employee 346917 at a station location in Effingham, reporting an undeclared aerosol shipment.  The shipment consists of 2 fiberboard boxes, each contained aerosol cans.  The shipment ending in -6972 contained 48 cans and the shipment ending in -6983 contained 12 cans.  Shipment -6972 was discovered by the distinct aerosol rattling as it was moved.  Being a part of a 2- piece mutilple shipment, the agents searched for the  second box and discovered shipment  -6983, also with the distinct rattling sound.  Additionally, shipment -6983 was also labeled "12 AEROSOL CANS" on one side and "CONTENTS IN AEROSOL CANS" on an adjacent side.  These packages were not marked and labeled in accordance with IATA Regulations.  The shipments are being held pending and IATA investigation.

XPO Logistics terminal NCH experienced a release of UN3495 Iodine from a 100.5-pound fiber drum. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup operations. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed that approximately ½ a pound of product released to a 2’ x 1’ area of the trailer floor. The fiber drum was punctured by a forklift blade. All released material along with the damaged drum was collected and containerized into a 55-gallon plastic drum. All waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column42: PETROLEUM DISTILLATES, N.O.S. OR PETROLEUM PRODUCTS, N.O.S.
column168: The KAG West, LLC driver was attempting to transfer petroleum distillates from one tank trailer into another tank trailer. During the process, one of the compartments on the trailer was overfilled. This allowed approximately 20 gallons of product to be released. Graymar Environmental responded to the scene and handled the remediation.
column169: KAG West, LLC will continue to train and enforce safe loading/unloading polices and procedures.

column168: The Kenan Transport, LLC driver was delivering diesel fuel into the customer's storage tank. During the course of the delivery, the fill pipe on the customer's storage tank broke loose. This caused the connection between the hose adaptor and the storage tank to become compromised. Approximately 15 gallons of diesel fuel was released. Remtech Environmental responded to the scene and handled the remediation.
column169: Kenan Transport, LLC has notified the customer of the issues with their storage tank so the necessary repairs can be completed.

AFTER TRIAGAING THE BOX, DR DETERMINED THE LEAKER WAS A 1 GALLON BUCKET OF BENJAMIN MOORE ULTRA SPEC 500 INTERIOR PAINT - FLAT WHITE. DR FOUND THE SAFETY DATA SHEET (SDS) AND PER SECTION 14 OF THE SDS, THAT PRODUCT IS NOT REGULATED. DR ALSO FOUND 5 AEROSOL CANS THAT STATED KNOX PAINT COMPANY - STONE WHITE. DR ALERTED RESPONSIBLE MANAGEMENT PERSON (RMP) WHO PROCEEDED TO CONTACT THE HAZARDOUS MATERIALS SERVICE CENTER (HMSC). AFTER SPEAKING WITH TARA, A HMSC REPRESENTATIVE, THIS SHIPMENT WAS DEEMED AS UNDECLARED.

column168: On March 10, 2023, eleven (11) five-gallon pails of  HS Enamel L/F C/F Green (UN1263) arrived with faulty seams and released approximately five (5) gallons of product to the trailer floor. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from Thin Line Environmental (TLE) to remediate the impacted surface. TLE personnel wiped down the undamaged cargo with absorbent pads and re-palletized them for continued shipping. The crew utilized granular absorbents and hand tools to collect and containerize all paint impacted material in one (1) 55-gallon drum and two (2) 85-gallon overpacks for disposal by R+L.

SequenceEvent: The package made it to a van and was loaded on to the van. We were informed by the belt manager shortly after it was loaded that the top of the package looked wet. It leaked out into the box and contaminated all 3 bottles of this hazmat package. We placed this into a lined hazmat tote and moved it to the hazmat cage. DescribePack: 1 loose cap had a 1/16 inch hole in the paper seal which led to the leakage. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: We were able to respond quickly to the radio call that there was a potential leaking hazmat on a van. We removed the package upon inspection and isolated this in the hazmat cage.

SequenceEvent: Package was discovered by the Driver of Work Area 224, [PII - REMOVED BY GEM], whom noticed the package was leaking once brought back to the station after an attempt to deliver was made & no one was home to receive. Once driver noticed, he called the station in which P&D Manager Zach Dorsey had come out to the truck, examined the package & gathered the necessary safety equipment. Placed the hazmat package in a yellow drum to remove from vehicle and then applied absorbent on the leakage. Once dried they swept the truck clear of any leakage. After the cleanup, they took the damaged hazmat to the hazmat cage for processing. DescribePack: Package failure was due to loose caps. There was nothing inside the package to prevent excessive damage or anything to ensure the caps would not loosen. DurationRel: 5 and MitigateEffect: Using absorbent to contain and easily remove the leakage & also placing the hazmat in a yellow drum to contain it.

column42: SULFURIC ACID WITH MORE THAN 51 PERCENT ACID
column168: Our driver began in Valmy, NV. Drove to Carlin NV and proceeded to load sulfuric acid at Loading Dock TK-49. Our driver successfully completed loading. But while he was securing his dome lid, he hand-tightened the lid and failed to follow with his wrench. Our belief is that the T-bolts may have been secured at that moment, but eventually, due to vibration, rattled loose. That would explain the delayed release of product. While traveling west on the I-80, there are no major turns until the driver came to his destination exit. This is where event happened. No trace of further product on the roadway, besides Phoenix Mine property. All remediation on Mine property was handled in-house. An employee drove the route and searched for other signs of spillage. Traces only found on exit ramp and NGM property. Driver discovered he was leaking upon arrival to NGM property while badging into property. The driver investigated and secured tanker. Response teams remediated area. The NRC, NVHP, and NGM were notified of the incident. We've called Envirocare out of Elko to help with the remediation. Shortly after the incident, it began to rain and eventually snowing. Area samples taken by Envirocare suggested acid has been somewhat neutralized.
column169: Recurrence prevention Drivers are adequately trained for the sensitive jobs they do. I would like to review procedures and make sure drivers are getting the most up to date information. Randomly audit drivers' procedure to ensure procedures are followed and being proactive on complacency.

column168: On 03/31/2023 at 0947 hours EST CSXT personnel in the Southover Yard (Savannah, GA) discovered PROX77233, a loaded tank car of Xylene leaking from bottom of the tank car. The car was isolated and the shipper, Eastman Chemical Company, was notified. HEPACO, a CSXT response contractor, responded and found product leaking from the Bottom Outlet Valve (BOV). HEPACO's assessment of the BOV found that product leaking through the body of the valve despite the valve being in the fully closed position. Responders were able to tighten the secondary closure cap on the BOV assembly one full turn using a wrench; this tightening of the secondary closure cap stopped the release. The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper's representative (Lauren Bailey 903-738-4160).  PROX77233 was held out of transportation pending load transfer, clean and purge, and receipt of OTMA.

Environmental  Remediation  &  Recovery  was dispatched  to  the  site.  Upon  the  contractor’s  arrival,  personnel  observed  that  the  released  material impacted  a  10ft-by-12ft  area  of  the  concrete  terminal  floor  and  estimated  that  fifteen  (15)  gallon  of material was released. Environmental Remediation & Recovery personnel stated that the material was released from a 275-gallon poly tote due to a forklift accident. Environmental Remediation & Recovery personnel transferred the remaining material from the damaged tote to a new tote to be shipped on to the consignee.  The contractor deployed granular absorbents to the impacted area and collected the spent material and containerized it in two (2) 55-gallon poly drums along with the cut-up damaged poly tote.    The  generated  waste  staged  onsite  at  the  terminal  prior  to  the  contractor  demobilizing.  The generated waste will remain onsite for the ESTES DGRM team to coordinate disposal.

On March 13, 2023, one (1) 330-gallon tote containing UN1760 was punctured by a forklift and released approximately 230-gallons of product to the trailer floor, concrete parking lot, and adjacent cargo. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from Thin Line Environmental (TLE) to remediate the impacted surfaces. TLE personnel transferred the contents of the damaged tote into one (1) new 275-gallon tote for continued shipping. The crew then utilized absorbents, degreasing agent, and hand tools to collect and containerize all UN1760 impacted material in thirty five (35) 35-gallon drums for disposal. All undamaged cargo was wiped down and repalletized for continued shipment.

column168: Truck and a bulk tanker containing a load of UN1993 Flammable Liquid was in route from Corpus Christi TX to Fredonia KS. While in route the truck ran off of the road which resulted in a rollover. As a result of the rollover, there was a very small drip from the dome lid on the tanker. There was also a small spill of motor oil that came from the truck engine. Local Fire Department and state police reported to the scene. Also, an emergency response and remediation crew was dispatched to the scene for cleanup, remediation and load transfer. The load was successfully transferred to another truck and transported on to the original destination. The site was cleaned and contaminated soil was disposed of properly.

column168: The KAG Energy, LLC driver was attempting to deliver gasoline into the customer's storage tank. The driver failed to connect the vapor recovery hose to the storage tank. This appears to have caused the tank to over-pressurize and 60-70 gallons of gasoline was released. A portion of the spilled gasoline was able to migrate to a nearby storm drain and ultimately impact a nearby creek. The local fire department and Clean Harbors Environmental were on site and handled the remediation.

SequenceEvent: DENATURED ALCOHOL IN DOOR #3 TRAILER #836716 IN THE UNLOAD WAS LEAKING AND GOT ONTO THE UNLOADER'S RIGHT HAND. column168: Veolia picked the drum on 3/2/23 from the shipper and was shipped to Veolia's 10 day intrasit facility in Fremont, CA. The drum was loaded onto a trailer to proceed to its final destination and was received at the Veolia Richmond TSDF on 3/9.  The facility began the offloading process on 3/14/23.  When they opened the trailer, they noticed a cubic yard box laying on its side and a drum missing a lid. The contents of the drum was on the top of surrounding drums along with visible staining on the nearby walls of the trailer and cubic yard boxes. It appeared there was a chemical reaction which generated pressure inside the drum which eventually led to the top flying off and causing the cubic yard box which was loaded directly on top of the drum to flip. Veolia believes that during transportation from the Veolia Fremont transfer facility to the Richmond site, agitation occurred in which allowed for a chemical reaction causing the pressure to build up and likely the rupture of the drum was instant.   Veolia personnel offloaded the trailer and thoroughly wiped down the drums along with the trailer.  The drum along with all spill clean up debris was containerized into a salvage drum.
column169: After talking with the shipper, Veolia believes the contents of the material was not the actual material shipped and it was improperly prepared for shipment. We believe that the material contained aluminum powder that was not reacted properly prior to shipment. The shipper failed to add enough water to properly react the aluminum powder and some aluminum powder was in clumps which did not react prior to shipment.  During the course of the shipment these clumps separated which allowed for water/moisture to react with the aluminum powder which caused the drum to pressurize and eventually rupture.   Veolia has spoken with the shipper and at this time all shipments are on hold until they have agreed to changes in their process. Veolia has notified the shipper of our findings and have requested that all their personnel will be properly trained. We are requesting certification of these training records. Additionally, Veolia has put safe guards in place so that Veolia personnel will need to verify that that the aluminum powder has properly reacted by agitating of the drum and leaving the material on site at the shipper's location for a week to make sure no further reaction will occur. Veolia is still finalizing the process with the shipper but we expect them to meet these conditions or otherwise Veolia will refuse to transport this material in the future.

column168: Unsecured freight

One of the containers (a 275-gallon tote) failed in the warehouse and released its entire contents inside the warehouse. The release was discovered on Monday, March 13, 2023.  Notifications were made to WL Black, Broker of Record for the generator, the waste generator and to SE/EO management. SE/EO responded immediately to the release that was contained within the building, deployed spill sorbents and dispatched a cleanup crew and safety representatives. A team of 1 response supervisor, 3 environmental response technicians, 2 site staff and a safety officer and HSE manager responded to the event. The broker/generator provided copies of profile for Nickle plating waste and SDSs for components believed added to one or more containers that had been shipped. Samples of the small amount of waste remaining in the failed tote were collected. These samples were noted to exhibit off-gassing and buildup of pressure within the closed sample container. The other containers appeared to be stable on inspection. Once spread of the release had been secured and contained, SE/EO collected as much of the spilled material as practicable using an empty vacuum truck and cleaned up the waste using granular sorbents, pads and booms. The work team utilized air monitoring equipment and work teams donned USEPA Level C Personal Protective Equipment (PPE) to ensure the safety the work team members during cleanup. The waste, cleanup material and PPE were containerized by placing the waste in one (1) tote (original waste liquid/washwater/surfactant), five (5) drums (granular sorbents, rags and pads) and four (4) drums (sorbent booms and PPE). A mild surfactant (Simple Green) was applied to the affected warehouse floor areas and the affected areas power washed with clean water. All cleaner/washwater was collected and placed into the liquid containing tote noted above.

Yard personnel reported a strong odor of alcohol near intermodal tank SNEU 145307.  Upon inspection of the tank, the air valve was found in the open position with the valve plug not installed.  The valve was closed stopping the release, and the plug was installed.

On March 29 a damaged drum was found leaking on the PM sort belt.  the drum contained UN3082 Environmentally Hazardous Substance, liquid, n.o.s., 9, PGIII.  A small amount leaked out of what appears to be a dented chime.  The damaged package was place d into a steel salvage drum and the shipper contacted for an amended shippers declaration.

column168: Team member was offloading a 25 yard vacuum box from the roll-off truck, and when it was fully tipped up on the rails, it started to leak. The material was chromium contaminated liquid / sludge, and liquid started to leak out of the top of the vacuum box door through the top seal (approximately 30 gallons total). They were able to get the box on the ground and the leaking stopped. The binder chains the secure the door were stuck inside the door, compromising the seal/gasket at the top of the door. After investigation, it was determined that the container had been delivered to the customer that way, and had been filled that way. It did not initially leak during loading because the material was mostly sludge. During transport, the solids settled, leaving more liquid on the top of the box. The material that leaked was cleaned up internally as it was at a TSDF with a response crew. The spill occurred inside of a containment area, and did not require further environmental reporting.
column169: The cause of the leak was totally human error, and it has been addressed with all the team members at the service center. The incident is also being discussed at higher levels within the organization so we do not have similar incidents at any other service centers.

column168: A truck driver punctured a metal drum of CORVE8300 -Viny Ester Resin with the forklift when he placed a pallet on the trailer's floor. He did not realize that he had punctured the drum before leaving the Tulsa, Oklahoma, facility. A few hours later, another truck driver flagged him down and pointed out that something was leaking from the trailer. Our truck driver stopped on the side of the road and called the Operations Manager. The Operations Manager notified the NAC Vice President of Operational and Regulatory Affairs. He contacted Clean Harbors Environmental Services, Inc. ("Clean Harbors"), the designed emergency response contractor. A cleanup crew was dispatched to the scene. Clean Harbors will manage the disposal of the cleanup debris.  What Failed - Code 104- Body  How Failed - Code 309 - Punctured  Causes of Failure 515- Human Error- Rushing, Mind Not on Task, Eyes Not on Task 516- Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object- The truck driver punctured the body of the metal drum containing the vinyl ester resin with the forks of the forklift during loading.
column169: The lessons learned include: (a) Do not rush! Rushing causes accidents! Taking your time and and being safe will save time. (b) Keep the pallet low when carrying it with the forklift. (c) The Operations Manager should note on the job observation safety checklist when an employee rushes, take short-cuts, or commits an unsafe act.

column168: On March 30; 2023, TAG inspected LTIA 329610, booking SEA 912229. This load sailed southbound on the Midnight Sun, voyage 23046 that departed Anchorage, AK on March 26th, 2023. Upon inspection, TAG found one box marked"Rustoleum Clear Garage Coating" labeled as limited quantity. According to the SDS, this material is hazardous and is classified as UN3066, class 8, PGII, paint or paint related material, corrosive liquid. This item was not included on the bill of lading when submitted to Anchorage and the trailer sailed with undeclared hazardous material. For the safety of our vessel crew and longshore, it is imperative hazardous loads are properly manifested.
column169: The bill of lading for this shipment in question was not completed correctly by Lynden's shipper. The hazardous material label was not caught by Lynden and bill of lading corrected by myself or a supervisor before it was loaded Southbound. The incident was reviewed with the people that were directly involved. Lynden has and will continue to cover proper hazardous identification and declaration with their drivers, dock workers, customer service team and supervisors in our daily safety meetings.

Damaged in transit

On 3/31/2023 a Veolia employee from the Newington, CT office was unloading drums into a trailer at the Veolia, Schenectady, NY ten day intransit facility when an employee noticed that a 55-gallon steel drum leaked in the transport vehicle. The shipment was picked up from the customer by Veolia on 3/31/2023 and then driven to the Veolia, Schenectady office on 3/31/2023. When the shipment arrived, a 55 gallon drum containing sodium hydroxide solid had a cover that was not secured properly. In addition there was liquid in the drum that spilled out the open lid onto the floor of the box van. The drum was sealed properly by fixing the lid so that it could continue transportation to the ultimate disposal facility.     The drum leaked about 1/2 gallon of class 8 material sodium hydroxide solution. The liquid was cleaned up with spill pads and absorbent and the lid on the drum was repositioned properly to prevent it from spilling. The duration of release is anticipated to be about 3 hours and an estimated 1/2 a gallon of sodium hydroxide solution leaked. The drum was still substantially full when the leak was discovered. No material made is outside the vehicle.
column169: The Veolia employee responsible for the shipment was instructed to assure that containers that have liquid in it must be shipped in appropriate packaging and that lids must be checked to ensure proper closure prior to transportation.

column168: UTLX 679959 was observed by Mechanical Department personnel with a small steady stream of liquid coming from the threads of the BOV cap.  Car moved to isolation track and response contractor called to investigate.  Tightened BOV cap and release slowed to a fast drip. Cycled BOV multiple times and leak did not stop or slow further.  BOV was very hard to operate.  Contents of UTLX 679958 was transferred to another tank car.  BOV cap/auxiliary valve assembly was removed and found the primary BOV would not close completely.  Gasket in BOV cap was deteriorated and packed with sludge.  Score marks observed in metal of ball valve of primary BOV.

column168: On March 23, 2023 at 1744 hrs., 2 CN Mechanical employees were walking next to CN Mays yard track NM05 and smelled an odor. They immediately experienced, difficulty breathing, tightening of chest and irritation of the eyes. The CN DGO was notified and responded.  When the DGO arrived and approached the area, he observed vapors coming from the top of railcar DBCX 201581. The DGO also observed liquid streaming down the sides and onto the ground.  Upon closer investigation, liquid was observed coming from the combination housing. The combination housing was secured by seal # A3784563. The seal was removed and the combination housing opened. Liquid was observed coming from the base of the liquid line valve were it connects to the pressure plate. The valve was able to be shifted by hand. Heavy corrosion was observed on the liquid line valve fastener bolts.  The internal pressure was relieved which stopped the release of product. The liquid line valve bolts were able to be tightened, which secured the liquid line valve to the pressure plate.
